<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-082-030  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 082 030.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Feb 13 1989 n525 p35(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Interpreter bows: hears Japanese, speaks English. (MatsushitaElectric product development)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sakurai, Miyoko.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Matsushita Electric demonstrates a limited but near-real-timeJapanese-to-English speech interpretation system that isspeaker-independent, requires no pre-training to voices and caninterpret sentences constructed with a 50-word Japanesevocabulary.andP;  The system recognizes fluidly-spoken Japanese speechin real-time and outputs clear and relatively natural Englishspeech in five to 10 seconds.andP;  The interpreter consists of a Sunworkstation, translation software developed at Carnegie-Mellon'smachine translation laboratory, and three circuit boardscontaining: a digital signal processor (DSP) for sound analysis, aDSP for determining voice similarity and a 16-bit microprocessorfor handling phonemes.andP;  The demonstration system is targeted atdoctor-patient conversations.andP;  Matsushita intends to create anotebook-sized system by 1993.andP;  A major problem to be overcome issusceptibility to noise.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Matsushita Electric Corporation of America (product development).andO;Topic:     Research and DevelopmentIntegrated SystemsProduct DevelopmentNew TechniqueLanguage TranslationJapanese LanguageVoice Recognition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>